<p>If you don't want to use JavaScript, you can use the radiobox method (utilizing <code>:checked</code> state and CSS adjacent selectors) to make it work without JavaScript. Markup is similar but the tab div goes into a wrapping <code>&lt;label&gt;</code>. Just before the <code>&lt;label&gt;</code> you need to place the <code>&lt;input type="radio"&gt;</code>. Make sure you point the <code>&lt;label&gt;</code> to the correct corresponding <code>&lt;input&gt;</code> by matching the <code>id</code> and <code>for</code> attributes.</p>

<p>With this method, since tab refers to the radiobox's <code>checked</code> state for determining selected state, you don't need to manually add <code>.selected</code> class on tabs. Convenient!</p>

<p>If you want to disable one of the tabs, add a <code>disabled</code> attribute on corresponding <code>&lt;input&gt;</code> not tabs.</p>

